{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609391"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16103"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16103"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.37,0.3,0.23,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8794"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEarly pregnancy loss is a common occurrence, with genetic factors playing a significant role. Approximately half of all spontaneous miscarriages are attributed to chromosomal variations in the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following represents the gestational age by which most spontaneous miscarriages have occurred?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1 week gestation","4 weeks gestation","7 weeks gestation","12 weeks gestation","20 weeks gestation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch has shown that \u003Cstrong\u003E7 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E marks the point by which approximately 70% of spontaneous miscarriages have occurred. This timing correlates with critical periods of embryonic development and organogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt \u003Cstrong\u003E1 week\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E4 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E gestation, pregnancy may not yet be detected, making it difficult to accurately document losses at these stages. While pregnancy loss can occur at \u003Cstrong\u003E12 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E20 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E gestation, these later losses are less frequent as pregnancies that reach these stages have typically overcome the highest risk period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChromosomal abnormalities, which account for approximately 50% of early pregnancy losses, typically cause developmental arrest during early embryogenesis, leading to miscarriage during the first trimester.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The majority of pregnancy losses occur during early embryonic development, with most happening before 7 weeks gestation","Genetic abnormalities represent the primary cause of early pregnancy loss, being responsible for half of all spontaneous miscarriages","Once a pregnancy progresses beyond the first trimester, the probability of miscarriage significantly diminishes"],"references":["Larsen EC, Christiansen OB, Kolte AM, Macklon N. New insights into mechanisms behind miscarriage. BMC Med. 2013 Jun 26;11:154. doi: 10.1186/1741-7015-11-154. PMID: 23803387; PMCID: PMC3699442.","Al-Alami Z, Abu-Huwaij R, Hamadneh S, Taybeh E. Understanding Miscarriage Prevalence and Risk Factors: Insights from Women in Jordan. Medicina (Kaunas). 2024 Jun 26;60(7):1044. doi: 10.3390/medicina60071044. PMID: 39064473; PMCID: PMC11279235.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16103"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60064"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T07:45:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T07:46:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"